"     Written by the doctors and editors at UpToDate",
"    </a>",
"    <div id=\"topicText\">",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H10434858\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       What causes knee pain?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Many different conditions can cause knee pain, including:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Bending or using the knee too much &mdash; This can cause pain in the front of the knee that worsens with running, climbing steps, or sitting for a long time.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Arthritis &mdash; Arthritis is a general term that means inflammation of the joints. There are lots of types of arthritis. The most common type, called osteoarthritis, often comes with age. It can cause pain, stiffness, and swelling (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef73149 \" href=\"UTD.htm?28/20/28993\">",
"         figure 1",
"        </a>",
"        ).",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Bursitis &mdash; Bursitis happens when fluid-filled sacs around the knee (called &ldquo;bursae&rdquo;) get irritated or swollen (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef59257 \" href=\"UTD.htm?26/2/26671\">",
"         figure 2",
"        </a>",
"        ). Bursitis can cause pain and swelling.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A collection of fluid in the knee &mdash; This can happen after a knee injury.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A tear in the meniscus &mdash; The meniscus is a cushion of rubbery material (cartilage) between the thigh bone and the leg bone (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef77293 \" href=\"UTD.htm?10/21/10578\">",
"         figure 3",
"        </a>",
"        ).",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A tear in a ligament &mdash; Ligaments are bands of tissue that connect 1 bone to another. There are 4 ligaments in each knee (",
"        <a class=\"graphic graphic_figure graphicRef77293 \" href=\"UTD.htm?10/21/10578\">",
"         figure 3",
"        </a>",
"        ).",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Muscle strain &mdash; Different leg muscles move the knee joint, causing the knee to bend and straighten. If 1 of these muscles doesn&rsquo;t work well, moving the knee can cause pain.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        A knee injury",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Conditions that don&rsquo;t involve the knee &mdash; For example, problems in the hip can sometimes cause knee pain.",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H10434865\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Is there anything I can do on my own to feel better?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;Yes. To ease your symptoms, you can:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Put ice on the knee to reduce pain and swelling &mdash; Put a cold gel pack, bag of ice, or bag of frozen vegetables on the injured area every 1 to 2 hours, for 15 minutes each time. Put a thin towel between the ice (or other cold object) and your skin. To reduce swelling, sit or lie down and raise your leg above the level of your heart when you put ice on it.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Rest your knee and avoid movements that worsen the pain &mdash; Try not to squat, kneel, or run. Also, don&rsquo;t use exercise machines, such as stair steppers or rowing machines. Instead, you can walk or swim (the front and back crawl strokes) for exercise.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Take a pain-relieving medicine, such as",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?19/35/20021?source=see_link\">",
"         acetaminophen",
"        </a>",
"        (sample brand name: Tylenol&reg;) or",
"        <a class=\"drug drug_patient\" href=\"UTD.htm?14/17/14614?source=see_link\">",
"         ibuprofen",
"        </a>",
"        (sample brand names: Advil&reg;, Motrin&reg;).",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H10434872\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       Should I see a doctor or nurse?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;See your doctor or nurse if:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bulletCompact-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        You are unable to put weight on your knee or your knee &ldquo;gives out&rdquo;",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Your knee is very swollen and painful",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        You have a fever with knee pain, swelling, and redness",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Your knee pain doesn&rsquo;t get better or gets worse after you treat it on your own for a few days",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
"     <p class=\"headingAnchor\" id=\"H10434879\">",
"      <span class=\"h1\">",
"       How is knee pain treated?",
"      </span>",
"      &nbsp;&mdash;&nbsp;The right treatment for knee pain depends on what is causing it. Treatments might include:",
"     </p>",
"     <p>",
"      <ul class=\"bullet-block\">",
"       <li>",
"        Wearing a knee brace or shoe insert",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Doing exercises to strengthen and stretch the muscles that move the knee joint &mdash; Ask your doctor or nurse which exercises can help with the cause of your pain.",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Having physical therapy",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Getting a shot of medicine in the knee",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Other medicines",
"       </li>",
"       <li>",
"        Surgery",
"       </li>",
"      </ul>",
"     </p>",
